"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147461","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-11-18","<p>Five public petitions on this subject have come to DCMS. We have been pleased to help some of the most striking sections of this poignant memorial, by purchasing them for the nation. The Government is pleased to have helped make it possible for these to be seen in different parts of the country before finding a permanent home in the Imperial War Museums.</p><p> </p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-11-18T12:44:58.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147461/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147461/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147461/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-10","World War I: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what representations his Department has received on extending the Blood Swept Lands and Seas of Red poppy installation at the Tower of London beyond 11 November 2014.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","214029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147462","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-11-17","<p>Tackling nuisance calls is a priority for the Department. We continue to improve signposting information and advice for people wanting to make a complaint. This is mirrored across both regulators websites:</p><p><a href="http://consumers.ofcom.org.uk/phone/tackling-nuisance-calls-and-messages/" target="_blank">http://consumers.ofcom.org.uk/phone/tackling-nuisance-calls-and-messages</a> <a href="http://ico.org.uk/for_the_public/topic_specific_guides/marketing/calls" target="_blank">http://ico.org.uk/for_the_public/topic_specific_guides/marketing/calls</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Earlier this year, we published our Nuisance Calls Action Plan on 30th March 2014 to enforce existing regulations effectively. Our achievements to date and the work that is currently underway can be viewed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/nuisance-calls-consultation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/nuisance-calls-consultation</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, on 25 October 2014, we published our consultation that proposes to lower or remove the legal threshold for the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) to take action against offending organisations. By lowering or removing the legal threshold, the ICO will be able to issue more monetary penalties to organisations in breach of the regulations. The ICO also continues to work collaboratively with Ofcom as evidenced by their joint Action plan, last updated on 3 March 2014: <a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/consultations/silent-calls/joint-action-plan/" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/consultations/silent-calls/joint-action-plan</a></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-11-17T17:04:22.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147462/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147462/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147462/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-10","Direct Selling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the level of complexity of the system for people complaining about nuisance calls; and what assessment he has made of the potential merits of consolidating that system under one body.","false","Biography information for Richard Graham","Gloucester","Richard Graham","214082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147463","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-11-19","<p>A call being made by an automated dialler is not automatically a nuisance call, providing the organisation complies with the relevant legislation, such as the Privacy and Electronic Communications Regulations (PECR) that specifically relates to sales and marketing calls.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A ban on the use of automated telephone dialling technology has therefore not been considered necessary by Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-11-19T13:50:09.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147463/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147463/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147463/answer","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147463/answer/previousversion/28632","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-10","Direct Selling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of banning the use of automated telephone dialling technology in order to prevent nuisance calls.","false","Biography information for Richard Graham","Gloucester","Richard Graham","214083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147464","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-11-18","<p>The Government fully supports the Royal British Legion’s Every Man Remembered website project. This project encourages those alive today to remember all the men and women who lost their lives in the First World War, using data provided by the Commonwealth War Graves Commission.</p><p> </p><p>The Legion is effectively disseminating such information through its local branches and associated publicity campaigns, alongside encouraging schools and other community groups to help remember the remaining 977,172 servicemen who have yet to be commemorated. I am pleased to note that DCMS has offered assistance with the Legion’s communication strategy.</p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-11-18T14:01:49.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147464/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147464/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147464/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-10","World War I: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will take steps to disseminate information on the Royal British Legion Every Man Remembered database and encourage further commemorate projects.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","214142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147465","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-21","<p>During the planning, implementation and conclusion of training, the Ministry of Defence (MOD) worked closely with the Cabinet Office, Home Office, Foreign and Commonwealth Office, Libyan command and supervisory team, Defence Section of the Libyan Embassy in London, Cambridgeshire Police and the MOD Police. In particular, we worked closely with the Home Office, Libyan Defence Section and Libyan command and supervisory team to return trainees who withdrew during the programme and once training had concluded.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","214130","2014-11-21T11:02:43.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147465/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147465/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147465/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147465/answer/previousversion/29081","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Libya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions his Department has had with (a) the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and (b) the Home Office on the decision to return 90 Libyan recruits from Bassingbourn; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","214127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147466","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-20","<p>Royal Navy recruiting staff attend national events promoting technical careers throughout the year. The two most prominent of these are 'Big Bang' UK Scientists and Engineers Fairs, and Skills and WorldSkills events. In addition, the Royal Navy encourages all Engineer Officers to enrol in the STEMNET Ambassadors scheme, the purpose of which is to match serving personnel with the STEM needs of local education establishments.</p><p>The Royal Navy is also strongly committed to the University Technical College programme; this scheme is technically focussed, offering a blend of education and vocational qualifications related to STEM areas.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-11-20T16:59:27.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147466/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147466/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147466/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Navy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will take steps to promote the Royal Navy as a career to pupils studying STEM subjects in further education.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","214148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147467","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-21","<p>The additional costs of the recent training programme for Libyan Armed Forces personnel is given in the attached table:</p><p> </p><p>The Libyan government has agreed to reimburse the Ministry of Defence for these costs. They have already paid £2.5 million, and we will continue to negotiate with them over paying the balance.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, small numbers of Libyan Armed Forces have been trained in UK staff colleges over the last three years and in Libya by the Defence Advisory Team. These activities cost approximately £0.5 million in financial year (FY) 2012-13 and approximately £1.7 million in FY 2013-14. The forecast for this activity in FY 2014-15 is £0.2 million.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","213247 ; 213248 ; 213336 ; 213337 ; 213404 ; 213854","2014-11-21T11:01:31.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147467/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147467/answer","213404 - Costs to UK for Training of Libyan Service Personnel.doc","Costs to UK of Training Libyan Service Personnel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147467/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147467/answer/previousversion/28361","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Libya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much the Government charged the government of Libya for training Libyan forces; and how much of that amount has been received.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","214166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147468","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-04","<p>Prior to the start of General Purpose Force training on 11 June 2014, the UK had numerous discussions with the Libyan government on the selection and vetting of Libyan trainees. These conversations included the United States and Italy. The Libyan government provided trainee candidates who had been through Libyan vetting and selection processes. These candidates were subject to additional UK vetting in Libya to ensure those selected met Foreign Office, Ministry of Defence and Home Office requirements on security, immigration, medical, physical, literacy, and numeracy criteria as well as meeting a distribution of trainees that was geographically representative of Libya. Home Office visa processes included checks against UK criminal databases and a visa declaration by all trainees that confirmed they held no criminal convictions or charges in the UK or elsewhere. We are not aware that any of those candidates who passed UK screening had criminal convictions or faced charges at that time in the UK or elsewhere.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-12-04T16:10:51.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147468/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147468/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147468/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147468/answer/previousversion/29088","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Libya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department took to vet Libyan personnel prior to their commencing military training at Bassingbourn barracks; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","214126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147469","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-11","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer I gave on 4 December 2014 to Question 213262 to the hon Member for Wrexham (Mr Ian Lucas).</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-12-11T17:35:02.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147469/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147469/answer","HOC214128  4 December 2014.doc","Hansard Extract 4 December 2014","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147469/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147469/answer/previousversion/29079","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Libya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what walking-out policy was in place in respect of Libyan recruits being trained at Bassingbourn; what oversight role was played by his Department; what the role of service police was in supervising those recruits; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","214128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147470","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-18","<p>Prior to the start of General Purpose Force training on 11 June 2014, the UK had several discussions with the Libyan government about the selection and vetting of the Libyan trainees. These conversations also included representations from the United States and Italy.</p><p> </p><p>The Libyan government provided trainee candidates who had been through Libyan vetting and selection processes. These candidates were then subject to additional UK vetting in Libya, to ensure that those selected met Foreign and Commonwealth Office, Ministry of Defence and Home Office requirements on security, immigration, medical, physical, literacy and numeracy criteria; in addition, the selected cohort comprised a suitable geographic representation of Libya. Home Office visa processes included checks against UK criminal databases and a visa declaration by all trainees which confirmed that they held no criminal convictions or charges in the UK or elsewhere.</p><p> </p><p>We are not aware that any of those candidates who passed UK screening had criminal convictions or faced charges at that time in the UK or elsewhere.</p><p> </p><p>During the course of training the Libyan General Purpose Force (GPF) we are aware of sixteen individuals being arrested. Of these five have been remanded in custody while facing the following criminal charges:</p><p> </p><p>Three counts of sexual assault, one count of theft of a pedal cycle and one count of exposure.</p><p> </p><p>Three counts of sexual assault and one count of theft of a pedal cycle.</p><p> </p><p>Two counts of sexual assault, one count of theft of a pedal cycle and one count of using threatening/abusive/insulting words/behaviour to cause harassment/alarm/distress against a police officer.</p><p> </p><p>One count of rape.</p><p> </p><p>One count of rape.</p><p> </p><p>All other trainees at Bassingbourn have been returned to Libya.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A team has been set up to produce for the Defence Secretary before Christmas an objective report into the GPF training. It is led by a MOD senior civil servant who was not involved in the original work, supported by a senior civil servant loaned from another Government Department to provide an additional element of independence and challenge.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","213338 ; 213410 ; 213412 ; 213588","2014-12-18T16:33:09.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147470/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147470/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147470/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147470/answer/previousversion/29077","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Libya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions his Department has had with (a) the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and (b) the Home Office on the behaviour of Libyan personnel on Bassingbourn base; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","214129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147471","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-21","<p>During the planning, implementation and conclusion of training, the Ministry of Defence (MOD) worked closely with the Cabinet Office, Home Office, Foreign and Commonwealth Office, Libyan command and supervisory team, Defence Section of the Libyan Embassy in London, Cambridgeshire Police and the MOD Police. In particular, we worked closely with the Home Office, Libyan Defence Section and Libyan command and supervisory team to return trainees who withdrew during the programme and once training had concluded.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","214127","2014-11-21T11:02:43.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147471/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147471/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147471/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147471/answer/previousversion/29075","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Libya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with (a) the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and (b) the Home Office on decisions to return Libyan personnel home because of events at Bassingbourn base; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","214130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147472","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-20","<p>Statistics showing enlistment into the Reserves are published by Defence Statistics in the Quarterly Personnel Report. The latest such report which shows figures at 1 October was published on 13 November.</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/uk-armed-forces-quarterly-personnel-report-2014</p><p>For ease of reference I am attaching the relevant page from this report.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2014-11-20T16:57:43.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147472/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147472/answer","UK armed forces quarterly personnel report- 1 October 2014.JPG","214131-UK Armed Forces Quarterly Personnel Report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147472/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Army Reserve","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many soldiers were enlisted in the Reserves from (a) April to September 2013, (b) April to September 2014, (c) July to September 2013 and (d) July to September 2014.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","214131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147473","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-20","<p>The Ministry Of Defence is committed to creating a diverse workforce which better represents the society that we defend. The Armed Forces recruitment campaigns are specifically designed to appeal to a full target audience, including women and Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic communities.</p><p>In addition to those recruitment campaigns, we recently established the Defence Diversity and Inclusion Programme to increase the diversity of the workforce, both military and civilian. We are currently devising the means by which our goals will be achieved. A key element of that programme relates specifically to recruitment.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-11-20T17:01:25.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147473/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147473/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147473/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Armed Forces: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to recruit more women and ethnic minorities to the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","214165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147474","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-20","<p>Yes, the Ministry of Defence does undertake reviews under Article 36 of Additional Protocol 1 to the 1949 Geneva Conventions. All new weapon systems, and any significant upgrades to existing system, are subject to a robust legal review.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-11-20T16:58:21.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147474/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147474/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147474/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if his Department will undertake reviews under Article 36 of Additional Protocol 1 to the 1949 Geneva Conventions before developing weapons systems capable of generating attack profiles.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Mr Tom Watson","214078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147475","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-17","<p>The Department has no plans to make a request to ISAF to publish, redacted or otherwise, the report of the investigation into the incident of 25 March 2011. As we have previously stated, an ISAF investigation was conducted and concluded that the actions of the Reaper crew had been in accordance with extant procedures and Rules of Engagement. Any request to seek the publication of this document should be made directly to the NATO Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-11-17T16:49:30.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147475/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147475/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147475/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Afghanistan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 20 March 2014 to Question 191671, and the recommendations of the Birmingham Policy Commission entitled The Security Impact of Drones, published on 22 October 2014, if his Department will request that ISAF publish, with any necessary redactions, the investigations report into the incident on 25 March 2011 in Afghanistan.","true","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Mr Tom Watson","214077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147476","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-18","<p>The Royal Navy has made no decision regarding the future deployment of unmanned aircraft systems (UAS) from the Queen Elizabeth Class carriers at this stage. The Royal Navy is, however, developing a Maritime UAS Strategy paper describing the requirement to 2050, and is working with industry on this issue.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-11-18T17:39:41.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147476/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147476/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147476/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his Department's policy is on basing (a) UK Reapers and (b) other remotely piloted aircraft on the Queen Elizabeth-class carriers.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Mr Tom Watson","214079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147477","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-20","<p>In February 2014 the Secretary of State approved an increase in the deployment of UK military Staff officers to UN missions, with costs being met through the Conflict Pool. Officials are currently working with the UN to fulfil this target.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-11-20T17:00:18.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147477/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147477/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147477/answer/previousversion/28360","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","United Nations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether he plans to increase the number of staff officers seconded to UN missions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","214058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147478","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-17","<p>From 2010 to 2014 the UK was assigned approximately 27 seconded staff officer posts within the UN system. Due to the differing tour lengths of each post and personnel overlaps it has not proven possible to provide an accurate number of personnel deployed in each post on an annual basis.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-11-17T17:10:01.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147478/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147478/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","United Nations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many staff officers of his Department were seconded to UN missions in each financial year from 2010-11 to 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","214059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147479","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-17","<p>Membership and engagement with multilateral organisations such as the UN, NATO and in some cases the EU, provide us with opportunities to achieve our security ends more efficiently and effectively than through bilateral channels alone - especially where we can combine efforts with like-minded countries<em>.</em> Various options related to the UK's future contribution to UN peacekeeping are currently being explored. These must be weighed against our role as the fifth biggest financial contributor to UN peacekeeping, our national interest and our ongoing national, bilateral, and multilateral obligations and commitments. Any decision to increase our contribution will be made with these factors in mind.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-11-17T16:46:51.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147479/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147479/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","United Nations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has to increase the UK's contribution to UN peacekeeping activities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","214060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147480","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-18","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not record the sales of each individual building; however we do record our disposal sales, which range from large defence sites to smaller parcels of land which are listed below by financial year (FY):</p><p> </p><p>FY2010-11 - 76</p><p>FY2011-12 - 100</p><p>FY2012-13 - 108</p><p>FY2013-14 - 97</p><p>FY2014-15 - 29 (up to 31 October 2014)</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-11-18T17:34:50.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147480/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147480/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147480/answer/previousversion/28366","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many buildings his Department sold in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013 and (e) 2014.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","213998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147481","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-18","<p>Ministry of Defence policy and procedures regarding the abrogation of contracts is through the use of Defence Condition 656 as published in the Acquisition Operating Framework which is available on the GOV.UK website: https://www.gov.uk/acquisition-operating-framework. The information requested is not held centrally and would require a manual check of all contracts let since 2010, which could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-11-18T17:41:27.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147481/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147481/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-10","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many contracts signed by his Department with suppliers of services or consultants include a clause providing that if the contract is abrogated by the Government, the provider or consultant will be compensated for lost income since 2010.","false","Biography information for Austin Mitchell","Great Grimsby","Austin Mitchell","214004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147482","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-11-19","<p>Discussions are ongoing with officials across all 39 Local Enterprise Partnerships on round two of Growth Deals. Heart of the South West LEP secured £118m from the Local Growth Fund in the first round of Growth Deals, which when combined with other investments produced a total package of £258m to support economic growth in the area.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-11-19T16:16:20.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147482/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147482/answer","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147482/answer/previousversion/28634","Biography information for Greg Clark","58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-11-10","Local Enterprise Partnerships: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, what discussions he has had with the Heart of the South West Local Enterprise Partnership about the timing and size of the second phase of local growth deals.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","213959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147483","Department for Education","false","2014-11-17","<p>Education has an important role to play in encouraging young people to build healthy relationships, and to identify those relationships which are unhealthy. Pupils may be taught about violence against men and boys in personal, social, health and economic (PSHE) education. PSHE can encompass many areas of study. It should equip pupils with the knowledge and skills to make safe and informed decisions and to prepare for adult life.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All schools should teach PSHE, drawing on good practice. This Government wants to support young people by ensuring teachers have effective materials to use in schools. We have asked the PSHE Association to develop guidance for schools on the topic of consent, and this is expected to be published by the end of 2014.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb","213929","2014-11-17T17:03:45.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147483/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147483/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-10","Domestic Abuse: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on educating boys about domestic violence against men and boys.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","213930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147484","Department for Education","false","2014-11-17","<p>Education has an important role to play in encouraging young people to build healthy relationships, and to identify those relationships which are unhealthy. Pupils may be taught about violence against men and boys in personal, social, health and economic (PSHE) education. PSHE can encompass many areas of study. It should equip pupils with the knowledge and skills to make safe and informed decisions and to prepare for adult life.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All schools should teach PSHE, drawing on good practice. This Government wants to support young people by ensuring teachers have effective materials to use in schools. We have asked the PSHE Association to develop guidance for schools on the topic of consent, and this is expected to be published by the end of 2014.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb","213930","2014-11-17T17:03:45.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147484/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147484/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-10","Violence: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on educating children about violence against men and boys.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","213929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147485","Department for Education","false","2014-11-17","<p>The Education Funding Agency wrote to all 16-19 institutions in October regarding our plans for announcing funding for 2015/16. We plan to confirm the national funding rate for 2015/16 in January 2015, as soon as we have early data on student numbers in 2014/15.</p><p> </p><p>After the national funding rate is confirmed, notification of individual institutions' budgets for 2015/16 (which will be based around the national funding rate) will be sent out in February or March.</p><p> </p><p>The level of funding for education of 16- to 19-year-olds beyond 2015/16 will be subject to the Government’s next spending review.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-11-17T14:38:35.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147485/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147485/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-10","Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans she has for the funding of (a) all post-16 education, (b) sixth forms and (c) further education colleges; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Mike Thornton","Eastleigh","Mr Michael Thornton","213941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147486","Department for Education","false","2014-11-17","<p>The information requested is not held centrally. An answer could only be provided at disproportionate cost, as we would need to review all departmental contracts.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is the Department for Education’s usual policy that contracts include a mutual, no faults termination clause which allows either party to terminate a contract by giving a period of notice. If the Department terminates such contracts under the ‘no faults’ clause we would reimburse the contractor for any committed or unavoidable cost, and would expect the contractor to take mitigating action to reduce such cost.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb",,"2014-11-17T17:01:30.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147486/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147486/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-10","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many contracts signed by her Department with suppliers of services or consultants include a clause providing that if the contract is abrogated by the Government, the provider or consultant will be compensated for lost income since 2010.","false","Biography information for Austin Mitchell","Great Grimsby","Austin Mitchell","214005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147487","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-17","<p /> <p>The Government believes reformed offenders can play a positive role in rehabilitating young and adult offenders through mentoring and demonstrating the possibility for change.</p><p> </p><p>Information is not held on the number of ex-offenders visiting the youth secure estate. Governors of Young Offender Institutions, Directors of Secure Training Centres and Managers of Secure Children’s Homes use their discretion to approve any visits to their individual establishments. Consideration will be given to the purpose of the visit, an assessment of the risk that the individual poses, and to wider responsibilities to ensure that young people are safeguarded at all times.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","214110","2014-11-17T17:47:41.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147487/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147487/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-10","Youth Custody","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer by the Minister for Prisons, Probation and Rehabilitation of 4 November 2014, to Question 213435, how many former offenders have been allowed to visit secure childrens' homes in each year since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","214109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147488","Department for Education","false","2014-11-20","<p>This information is not held by the Department for Education. Gender of school details are only collected by the Department at the point of first entry (i.e. age 11 for 11-18 schools). The information requested is held by local authorities or academies in each local authority area.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-11-20T15:36:39.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147488/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147488/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-10","Boarding Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 24 October 2014 to Queston 211886, how many of the co-educational state boarding schools in England are single sex up to sixth form; and how many of those schools accept only (a) boys and (b) girls until sixth form.","false","Biography information for Margot James","Stourbridge","Margot James","214116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147489","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-17","<p>Our academic institutions had a strong track record in attracting European research grants under the previous Framework Programme 7 (FP7), taking 25% of the higher education pot. The Government is keen to maintain this leadership with the FP7 successor, Horizon 2020. In partnership with Innovate UK and Local Enterprise Partnerships, we will work with our Higher Education Institutions and their representative bodies to ensure that they are aware of the opportunities and that they are supported through the processes. Horizon 2020 is much larger than FP7, with an allocation of €89bn over its seven years (compared to €53bn in FP7), and the widening of its scope to cover innovation is a good fit with UK policies for a knowledge economy.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-11-17T11:14:31.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147489/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147489/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-10","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to maximise drawdown of European research and innovation-related grants and other forms of investment for academic institutions.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","214161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147490","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-11-17","<p>The Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC) does not own the Freehold on any property and has therefore made no sales of this nature.</p><p>The Department leases property as below:</p><p> </p><p>A) 3 Whitehall Place, London (whole building) – due for lease-break review in 2021 (private landlord)</p><p> </p><p>B) 55 Whitehall, London (whole building) – due for review in 2070 (Crown property)</p><p> </p><p>C) Kings Buildings, London (three floors) – due for review in 2015 (public landlord)</p><p> </p><p>D) One Victoria Street, London (part of one floor) – due for review in 2015 (other Government Department as landlord)</p><p> </p><p>E) Atholl House, Aberdeen (two floors) – lease due to expire in 2016 (other Government Department as landlord)</p><p>As part of Cabinet Office property guidelines, Departments are required to vacate properties at the review date where possible. The preferred alternative is to share existing Government property with other Departments.</p><p>DECC has followed this guidance where applicable and will seek to vacate properties (C) and (D) above within 2015.</p><p>As the lease in property (E) expires in 2016 DECC have already started to consult with other Departments on the possibility of sharing existing buildings with ongoing leases in the city.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2014-11-17T17:02:37.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147490/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147490/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-10","Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many buildings his Department sold in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013 and (e) 2014.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","213999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147491","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-11-17","<p>The Department of Energy and Climate Change does not hold this information centrally and it can only be provided at a disproportionate cost. The Department’s standard terms and conditions include a cancellation clause which provides for termination upon giving the supplier 28 days’ notice. The Department endeavours to manage its relationship with suppliers fairly and complies with all contractual obligations applicable prior to any termination.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2014-11-17T15:53:30.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147491/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147491/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-10","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many contracts signed by his Department with suppliers of services or consultants include a clause providing that if the contract is abrogated by the Government, the provider or consultant will be compensated for lost income since 2010.","false","Biography information for Austin Mitchell","Great Grimsby","Austin Mitchell","214006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147492","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-11-19","<p>All countries are expected to come forward with their Intended Nationally Determined Contributions (INDCs) well ahead of the UNFCCC Conference of the Parties (COP) in December 2015. Countries are in most cases already taking action to reduce emissions. A credible assessment of the additional export potential related to INDCs is not possible, as INDCs that are yet to be determined.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2014-11-19T13:32:22.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147492/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147492/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-10","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment he has made of the potential economic contribution of the export of UK expertise in the climate change mitigation and adaption sector as a result of other states' efforts to meet Intended Nationally Determined Contributions commitments.","false","Biography information for Mr Mike Hancock","Portsmouth South","Mr Mike Hancock","213945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147493","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-11-25","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has discussed the negotiations for a new global climate deal, including countries’ Intended Nationally Determined Contributions (INDCs), with a large number of his international counterparts.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2014-11-25T15:09:42.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147493/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147493/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147493/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-10","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what bi-lateral discussions he has had with international partners on their Intended Nationally Determined Contributions before the 2015 UN Climate Change Conference; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Mike Hancock","Portsmouth South","Mr Mike Hancock","213946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147494","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-17","<p>We are currently undertaking monitoring of the insurance market for both households and small businesses. This will look at the availability of insurance, and the experience of small businesses in obtaining insurance cover in high flood risk areas.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-11-17T12:52:07.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147494/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147494/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-10","Floods: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has to assess the affordability of flood insurance for small businesses in flood hit areas following the expiry of the Statement of Principles between the Government and the Association of British Insurers.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","213979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147495","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-17","<p>The salary of the CEO of the Flood Re Scheme is a matter for the Directors of Flood Re who undertook the recruitment, and the Association of British Insurers whose members are currently funding the project set up costs including staff costs. It was determined by reference to current market rates for a reinsurance company. The salary will in future be funded from the Flood Re income and be disclosed in its annual report and accounts, which will be laid before Parliament as a public document.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-11-17T13:05:30.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147495/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147495/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-10","Floods: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the annual salary of the Chief Executive of the Flood Re scheme will be; how that salary was determined; and from what budget funding for that salary will be drawn.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","214055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147496","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-17","<p>We have interpreted ‘buildings’ to mean ‘sites’. A site can be made up of several of buildings.</p><p>The table below shows the number of sites sold by core Defra by financial year.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p></td><td><p>10/11</p></td><td><p>11/12</p></td><td><p>12/13</p></td><td><p>13/14</p></td><td><p>14/15 to date.</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of sites sold</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-11-17T15:45:30.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147496/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147496/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-10","Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many buildings her Department sold in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013 and (e) 2014.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","213997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147497","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-19","<p>The standard terms and conditions used by core Defra do not include compensation clauses in the event of termination of the contract. Reviewing all contracts signed since 2010 to identify possible exceptions to our standard terms would entail disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since January 2011, as part of the Government’s transparency programme, details of contracts worth over £10,000 are published online on Contracts Finder (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder). </a></p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-11-19T13:45:48.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147497/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147497/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147497/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-10","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many contracts signed by her Department with suppliers of services or consultants include a clause providing that if the contract is abrogated by the Government, the provider or consultant will be compensated for lost income since 2010.","false","Biography information for Austin Mitchell","Great Grimsby","Austin Mitchell","214007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147498","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-17","<p>The Government abhors animal cruelty but considers that there are laws in place enabling enforcers to take action when such suffering occurs.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-11-17T13:10:21.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147498/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147498/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147498/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-10","Pets: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what action the Government plans to take to address neglect, cruelty and abandonment of pets.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","214095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147499","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-17","<p>The RSPCA recently launched their manifesto which contains several suggestions for amending animal welfare legislation. In addition Defra also receives direct representations from the RSPCA for ways animal welfare legislation can be changed.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-11-17T13:09:06.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147499/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147499/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147499/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-10","Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent representations she has received from the RSPCA on updating animal welfare legislation.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","214097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147500","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-17","<p>The existing legislation in this area provides enforcers with powers to tackle complaints about poor welfare in breeding establishments and pet shops. The existing laws on the selling of pet animals apply to the commercial selling of animals over the internet for businesses based in this country. Defra has been working with the Pet Advertising Advisory Group (PAAG) and the main internet advertising sites who have adopted minimum standards for the on-line advertising of pet animals. Since PAAG launched the minimum standards last year (which were endorsed by Defra), over 100,000 inappropriate advertisements have been removed from the internet. Defra with PAAG will continue to press other internet sites to adopt the minimum standards and some sites will go further.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","214098","2014-11-17T13:19:09.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147500/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147500/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-10","Pets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if the Government will update legislation regarding the selling and breeding of pets to reflect the increased trade of pets on the internet.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","214076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147501","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-20","<p>Defra officials are currently working with Sub-Group members to finalise the Joint Action Plan with a view to publishing it as soon as possible.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-11-20T14:57:00.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147501/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147501/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147501/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-10","Birds of Prey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when she plans to publish the Uplands Stakeholder Forum hen harrier sub-group draft joint action plan.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bingham","High Peak","Andrew Bingham","214099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147502","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-17","<p>The existing legislation in this area provides enforcers with powers to tackle complaints about poor welfare in breeding establishments and pet shops. The existing laws on the selling of pet animals apply to the commercial selling of animals over the internet for businesses based in this country. Defra has been working with the Pet Advertising Advisory Group (PAAG) and the main internet advertising sites who have adopted minimum standards for the on-line advertising of pet animals. Since PAAG launched the minimum standards last year (which were endorsed by Defra), over 100,000 inappropriate advertisements have been removed from the internet. Defra with PAAG will continue to press other internet sites to adopt the minimum standards and some sites will go further.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","214076","2014-11-17T13:19:09.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147502/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147502/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147502/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-10","Pets: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if the Government will take steps to prevent the casual breeding and purchasing of pets to prevent subsequent abandonment and neglect.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","214098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147503","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-17","<p>Canals and rivers are an important asset for tourism and recreation, which the Government aims to protect and promote. However, the maintenance and dredging of canals and other waterways is an operational matter for the relevant Navigation Authority.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-11-17T13:08:41.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147503/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147503/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147503/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-10","Inland Waterways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that local waterways blocked by flooding are reopened for community use as soon as possible.","false","Biography information for Mr Mike Thornton","Eastleigh","Mr Michael Thornton","214094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147504","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-20","<p>It is for port operators to decide if they wish to provide border inspection facilities to facilitate the importation of regulated food products. Defra’s responsibility, with regard to imports of animal products, is to work with Port Health Authorities and the Food and Veterinary Office of the European Commission to ensure that such facilities meet EU standards. The Food Standards Agency fulfils a similar role for the approval of Designated Points of Entry for food of non-animal origin.</p><p>I recognise the importance of having an adequate network of inspection facilities. I would welcome representations from interested parties, if it is believed there is a problem with the current provision of such facilities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-11-20T11:25:37.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147504/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147504/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147504/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-10","Food: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she has taken to increase the number of ports with facilities for the inspection of imported food; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","214107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147505","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-20","<p>The Secretary of State chairs regular meetings with the Devolved Administrations on issues of mutual interest. The Secretary of State discussed dairy-related issues with Northern Irish MPs and MEPs earlier this week.</p><p>Defra officials also maintain regular contact with their counterparts in the Devolved Administrations on a range of dairy issues.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-11-20T15:03:28.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147505/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147505/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147505/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-10","Milk: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions she has had with the devolved administration on milk prices paid to farmers.","false","Biography information for Lord McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown","South Antrim","Dr William McCrea","214157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147506","Home Office","false","2014-11-17","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information centrally.<br><br>The Home Office is responsible for police recorded crime statistics, consisting of indictable and triable-either-way offences and does not include summary offences, such as poaching.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-11-17T17:02:31.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147506/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147506/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147506/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-10","Poaching","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many incidents of poaching have been recorded in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","214162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147507","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-17","The IAEA has verified in their 7 November 2014 Report on Iran’s nuclear programme that at Natanz, Iran has 1,008 IR-2M centrifuges installed but not operating, and 172 IR-2M centrifuges installed for research and development.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-11-17T15:14:37.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147507/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147507/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147507/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-10","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received on Iran's possession of IR-2M model centrifuges.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","214168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147508","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-19","<p>We take every opportunity to ensure the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea (DPRK) government is aware of our serious concern about the human rights situation in the DPRK, and we do specifically raise the incompatibility of its domestic law with international human rights law. On 9 October, the British Ambassador met the Deputy Director of the International Organisations Directorate of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Han Tae Sung, and underlined the strength of UK concern on this issue. In July, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office Director for Asia Pacific visited Pyongyang and, during meetings with the DPRK government and the Workers’ Party of Korea, called for serious progress to be made in improving the human rights situation in accordance with international law. On 28 August, the British Chargé d’Affaires in Pyongyang, together with other EU heads of mission, met DPRK Foreign Minister, Ri Su Yong, who indicated a willingness to engage in dialogue with the EU on human rights, which is being pursued.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2014-11-19T16:02:21.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147508/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147508/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147508/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-10","North Korea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions HM Embassy in the Democratic People's Republic of North Korea has had with the government of that country on the compatibility of international human rights law with domestic North Korean law.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","214139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147509","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-12-17","<p>On 7 November 2014, the IAEA Director General issued his latest report on the status of Iran’s nuclear programme. This report covers Iran's nuclear programme, the IAEA's efforts to address the Possible Military Dimensions of Iran’s nuclear programme (PMD), and the nuclear aspects of the Joint Plan of Action with the E3+3. The report is available on the IAEA’s website at http://www.iaea.org/sites/default/files/gov2014-62.pdf.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-12-17T13:52:58.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147509/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147509/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147509/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-10","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received on Iran's nuclear enrichment activities.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","214167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147510","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-17","<p>E3+3 and Iran are both committed to trying to reach a comprehensive agreement by 24 November. But there are still significant gaps between the parties. Reaching agreement by 24 November on these areas will be challenging. It will require Iran to accept reductions in the scale and scope of its programme.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-11-17T15:15:51.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147510/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147510/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147510/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-10","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received on Iran's commitment to agree a permanent nuclear agreement with the P5+1.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","214169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147511","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-17","We are deeply concerned by the detention of Ghancheh Ghavami, and have pressed the Iranian Government repeatedly over her welfare and our concerns about due process in her case. Both the Prime Minister and the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) discussed this matter with President Rouhani and Foreign minister Zarif respectively in September. The UK’s non resident Charge d’Affaires continues regularly to raise the case with his Iranian counterpart, including most recently on 9 November. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office is providing consular assistance to Ms Ghavami’s family at this difficult time.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-11-17T15:13:13.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147511/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147511/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/147511/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-10","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to protect the rights of Ghoncheh Ghavami in Iran.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Huppert","Cambridge","Dr Julian Huppert","214134"
