"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143381","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-10","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave him on 4 December 2014 to Question 213262.</p><p>http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=213262</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","214407","2014-12-10T17:30:17.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143381/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143381/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143381/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143381/answer/previousversion/28362","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-07","Libya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will initiate a formal review of the events which led to the recent suspension of UK training of Libyan troops.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","213896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143382","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-17","<p>The contract to build four Military Afloat Reach and Sustainability (MARS) Tankers was awarded to Daewoo Shipbuilding and Marine Engineering in March 2012. Although UK companies participated in the competition to supply the vessels, none submitted a final bid. Following the construction in South Korea, the ships will undergo customisation and trials in the UK, prior to entering service with the Royal Fleet Auxiliary. A competition for this package of work is under way, and is limited to UK companies. An announcement of the results of this competition, and on the contract for the provision of support for the ships, is expected in 2015.</p><p>The approved cost for the MARS Tanker project, including the cost of the vessels, and the customisation and trials is £596 million. There are currently no other plans for the procurement of Royal Fleet Auxiliary Tankers.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","213891 ; 213893","2014-11-17T17:10:52.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143382/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143382/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143382/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-07","Royal Fleet Auxiliary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what bids his Department has received from UK companies for the supply of four large fast fleet tankers for the Royal Fleet Auxiliary.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","213892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143383","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 24 March 2014, (Official Report, column 56W) to the hon. Member for Makerfield (Yvonne Fovargue).</p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","213897 ; 213898","2014-11-17T17:11:21.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143383/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143383/answer","Electronic Warfare.doc 24 March 2014..doc","Hansard Extract","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143383/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-07","Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many of the cyber reservists recruited are (a) regular personnel leaving the armed forces, (b) current and former reservists and (c) individuals with no previous military experience.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","213899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143384","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-17","<p>The contract to build four Military Afloat Reach and Sustainability (MARS) Tankers was awarded to Daewoo Shipbuilding and Marine Engineering in March 2012. Although UK companies participated in the competition to supply the vessels, none submitted a final bid. Following the construction in South Korea, the ships will undergo customisation and trials in the UK, prior to entering service with the Royal Fleet Auxiliary. A competition for this package of work is under way, and is limited to UK companies. An announcement of the results of this competition, and on the contract for the provision of support for the ships, is expected in 2015.</p><p>The approved cost for the MARS Tanker project, including the cost of the vessels, and the customisation and trials is £596 million. There are currently no other plans for the procurement of Royal Fleet Auxiliary Tankers.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","213892 ; 213893","2014-11-17T17:10:52.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143384/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143384/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143384/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-07","Royal Fleet Auxiliary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost is of the four large fast fleet tankers for the Royal Fleet Auxiliary being constructed in South Korea.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","213891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143385","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-17","<p>The contract to build four Military Afloat Reach and Sustainability (MARS) Tankers was awarded to Daewoo Shipbuilding and Marine Engineering in March 2012. Although UK companies participated in the competition to supply the vessels, none submitted a final bid. Following the construction in South Korea, the ships will undergo customisation and trials in the UK, prior to entering service with the Royal Fleet Auxiliary. A competition for this package of work is under way, and is limited to UK companies. An announcement of the results of this competition, and on the contract for the provision of support for the ships, is expected in 2015.</p><p>The approved cost for the MARS Tanker project, including the cost of the vessels, and the customisation and trials is £596 million. There are currently no other plans for the procurement of Royal Fleet Auxiliary Tankers.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","213891 ; 213892","2014-11-17T17:10:52.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143385/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143385/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143385/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-07","Royal Fleet Auxiliary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his future procurement plans for the Royal Fleet Auxiliary tankers are; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","213893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143386","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-17","<p>The UK will contribute a few hundred military personnel to the NATO train, advise and assist mission.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-11-17T16:45:59.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143386/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143386/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143386/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-07","Afghanistan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many members of the armed forces he expects to remain in Afghanistan as part of the training mission after 2014.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","213894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143387","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 24 March 2014, (Official Report, column 56W) to the hon. Member for Makerfield (Yvonne Fovargue).</p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","213898 ; 213899","2014-11-17T17:11:21.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143387/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143387/answer","Electronic Warfare.doc 24 March 2014..doc","Hansard Extract","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143387/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-07","Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many cyber reservists have been recruited to the Joint Cyber Reserve since September 2013.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","213897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143388","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 24 March 2014, (Official Report, column 56W) to the hon. Member for Makerfield (Yvonne Fovargue).</p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","213897 ; 213899","2014-11-17T17:11:22.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143388/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143388/answer","Electronic Warfare.doc 24 March 2014..doc","Hansard Extract","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143388/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-07","Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many cyber reservists his Department planned to recruit at the time of announcement of the creation of the Joint Cyber Reserve in September 2013.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","213898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143389","Department for Education","false","2014-11-17","<p>The model articles set out the arrangements for the election and appointment of parents to be directors of academy trusts. They provide discretion to directors of the trust to determine the terms of reference under which elections and appointments should be undertaken. The Department for Education has set out in the Governors’ Handbook the high professional standards which governors and directors are expected to meet. Academy trusts must ensure that directors are suitable and have the necessary skills and capacity to take on the role.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-11-17T17:31:09.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143389/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143389/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143389/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-07","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 24 October 2014 to Question 211249, what powers academy trusts have to pre-screen parent director candidates prior to election by parents; and what guidance her Department issues to academy trusts on such pre-screening.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Mr Liam Byrne","213838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143390","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-11-19","<p>It is National Grid’s responsibility to procure enough operating reserve as might be required for the real-time balancing of the system, which is a vital part of ensuring security of electricity supply. This includes fluctuations in wind and solar generation, as well as tripping of thermal and nuclear plant.</p><p>The Annual Energy Statement made by my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State on 6 November 2014 (<em>Official Report</em>, <em>Column 982-985</em>) sets out the range of actions the Government has taken to ensure security of electricity supply:</p><p><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmhansrd/cm141106/debtext/141106-0001.htm#14110630000001" target="_blank">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmhansrd/cm141106/debtext/141106-0001.htm#14110630000001</a>.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-11-19T13:33:03.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143390/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143390/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143390/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-07","Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether he has made an assessment of the availability of generators to back up fluctuations in wind and solar supply to ensure security of electricity supply.","false","Biography information for Lord Lilley","Hitchin and Harpenden","Mr Peter Lilley","213837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143391","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-17","<p>The Commission has proposed EU bass management measures for 2015, which will be considered at December Fisheries Council. As part of those discussions I will continue to press for an approach which will ensure bass stocks recover and become sustainable.</p><p><br></p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-11-17T10:35:08.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143391/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143391/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143391/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-07","White Fish: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will take steps to introduce at an EC level measures to reduce sea bass mortality by 80 per cent by 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","213849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143392","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-17","<p>As reported in the media, there was an explosion and consequent fire at the Parchin military complex, outside of Tehran in early October 2014. The explosion was not in the area of the high explosive test facility at Parchin referred to in IAEA Board of Governors’ reports. Permission for IAEA inspectors to access facilities at Parchin as required remains necessary to address international concerns about the possible military dimensions of Iran’s nuclear programme.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-11-17T15:36:40.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143392/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143392/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143392/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-07","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of recent reports of a large explosion at Parchin military complex in Iran.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","213844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143393","Department of Health","false","2014-11-19","<p>The Sign up to Safety campaign was launched on 24 June 2014. Each organisation that has joined the campaign has committed to improving patient safety through the implementation of a Safety Improvement Plan. The Safety Improvement Plan builds on the pledges the organisation set out when joining. The pledges are expanded in more detail in the plan, which sets out what the organisation wants to achieve and by when. Each organisation is expected to demonstrate how they will measure the local impact of their aims over the next three years via a measurement section within their plans. They will then implement their aims over the next three years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Sign up to Safety campaign is being promoted by means of:</p><p> </p><p>- a national campaign website;</p><p> </p><p>- regional and national presentations at events across the country delivered by the Campaign Director, the Secretary of State and others;</p><p> </p><p>- Twitter with over 1,500 followers;</p><p> </p><p>- a blog by the Campaign Director;</p><p> </p><p>- an online seminar programme (webinars);</p><p> </p><p>- through partner organisations including NHS England, Care Quality Commission, Monitor, NHS Trust Development Authority, NHS Litigation Authority, Health Education England, and NHS Improving Quality;</p><p> </p><p>- mini poster campaigns, such as the Safe Care Costs Less, and individual events, such as the launch of the Patient Briefing Video; and</p><p> </p><p>- through participant websites and local events.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As at the end of October 2014, a total number of 136 organisations have agreed to participate in the Sign up to Safety campaign. Each participant organisation is expected to set out how they will contribute to the campaign’s three year objective via their Safety Improvement Plan – they are expected to quantify the expected impact of their actions on a reduction of avoidable harm and saving lives. The measurement and evaluation of the impact at a regional and national level will be led by NHS England working with NHS Improving Quality as part of the integrated measurement strategy for both the campaign and the Patient Safety Collaborative programme. This will include the National Reporting and Learning System, harms via the Safety Thermometer and mortality rates, case studies of individual organisations and patient record reviews.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter","213870 ; 213872","2014-11-19T15:47:48.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143393/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143393/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/143393/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-07","Patients: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to promote the Sign up to Safety campaign; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Robert Neill","Bromley and Chislehurst","Robert Neill","213871"
